WEBVTT

00:05.339 --> 00:09.174
[radar pings]

00:10.544 --> 00:12.644
[pinging continues]

00:12.646 --> 00:16.749
<i> ¶¶ [ominous]</i>

00:22.356 --> 00:25.758
[seagulls cawing]

00:31.499 --> 00:34.366
"A blanket of naps
begets a handful of gnats,"

00:34.368 --> 00:36.368
is what my granddaddy
would say to me

00:36.370 --> 00:39.638
on egg and sausage mornings.

00:39.640 --> 00:42.674
Drink your water
in a tub full of bourbon.

00:48.282 --> 00:51.583
And why, for the matter of
scotch and my lady's crotch,

00:51.585 --> 00:54.720
do movies always act like
mermaids breathe water?

00:54.722 --> 00:58.257
Obviously mermaids are mammals
because they look part human,

00:58.259 --> 00:59.658
for goodness gracious,
righteous books,

00:59.660 --> 01:01.727
and boots of my ancestors' sake.

01:01.729 --> 01:03.529
Do they not?

01:05.266 --> 01:08.267
- Why do they have hair then?
- What?

01:08.269 --> 01:12.404
Why do mermaids have hair
if they live in the water then?

01:12.406 --> 01:15.140
Why the mermaid has hair
could be perhaps

01:15.142 --> 01:18.477
indeed for the same reason
why the walrus has a mustache.

01:19.680 --> 01:22.181
Why does a walrus
have a mustache?

01:22.183 --> 01:26.351
I don't know the answer to this,
but it does indeed.

01:26.353 --> 01:28.353
Sure as a jury
in a witch trial, they do.

01:28.355 --> 01:31.457
You think mermaids have...

01:31.459 --> 01:33.625
oh, have mustaches?

01:33.627 --> 01:37.296
Did you jump overboard
while I was talking?

01:37.298 --> 01:39.565
Do you think they really
have the coconut bras

01:39.567 --> 01:41.667
or, you know, those...

01:41.669 --> 01:44.269
those seashell bras?

01:44.271 --> 01:45.671
I think their tits are out.

01:45.673 --> 01:48.674
- You hope their tits are out.
- Yeah.

01:48.676 --> 01:51.677
Fish guts on your glass.

01:51.679 --> 01:53.345
Hold on.

01:55.583 --> 02:00.686
<i> [radio chatter]</i>

02:02.656 --> 02:06.258
[seagulls cawing]

02:06.260 --> 02:10.294
My niece entering kindergarten.

02:12.666 --> 02:14.600
So you don't think
sirens exist

02:14.602 --> 02:16.201
because no one
in their right mind

02:16.203 --> 02:18.303
would draw attention
to their death sentence.

02:18.305 --> 02:21.740
Exactly. Mermaids are
definitely not sirens.

02:21.742 --> 02:25.244
Would you seduce
a serial killer if you knew

02:25.246 --> 02:28.647
he was a serial killer
who also wanted to eat you?

02:28.649 --> 02:30.449
I don't think people
want to eat sirens.

02:30.451 --> 02:32.284
I think they want
to fuck sirens.

02:32.286 --> 02:34.419
Still in case in point
to be the same.

02:34.421 --> 02:35.821
No way sirens exist.

02:35.823 --> 02:37.523
But mermaids...

02:37.525 --> 02:41.627
Mermaids have been spotted
for a hundred years

02:41.629 --> 02:43.529
around these waters,

02:43.531 --> 02:45.397
surfacing to have a look,

02:45.399 --> 02:47.633
curiosity getting
the best of them.

02:47.635 --> 02:49.368
STANLEY: Maybe they
really do exist.

02:49.370 --> 02:51.737
Maybe they do.

02:51.739 --> 02:55.841
Maybe if we waited long enough,
say for a week or weeks on end,

02:55.843 --> 02:57.576
we could catch one surfacing,

02:57.578 --> 02:59.778
crawling out of the water
to have a look

02:59.780 --> 03:03.782
at the flickering lights
of the modern world.

03:03.784 --> 03:05.651
Maybe they're worth a fortune

03:05.653 --> 03:09.321
if you actually caught one
and cut off her tail.

03:10.624 --> 03:13.492
Why would you wanna
cut off a mermaid's--

03:13.494 --> 03:15.661
You don't know how strong
or resourceful a mermaid is.

03:15.663 --> 03:17.362
If she's survived this long,

03:17.364 --> 03:18.664
maybe she'd know
how to gnaw through the rope

03:18.666 --> 03:20.365
and release herself
from the boat.

03:20.367 --> 03:22.401
Logic and practicality
would dictate

03:22.403 --> 03:26.672
that one must maim
a mythical creature

03:26.674 --> 03:30.676
if one wants to transport
a mythical creature.

03:30.678 --> 03:32.377
Then how then?

03:32.379 --> 03:34.746
We take our fire ax
and chop her tail off,

03:34.748 --> 03:36.715
hack it off,

03:36.717 --> 03:39.284
tie the tail
to the end of the boat

03:39.286 --> 03:42.721
and drag it with us, underwater,
all the way back to shore,

03:42.723 --> 03:45.424
throw her human half into
the bloody chum hole,

03:45.426 --> 03:47.426
then we sell her in two pieces,

03:47.428 --> 03:50.529
and make
a million fucking dollars.

03:51.765 --> 03:53.298
Is the ax on the boat?

03:53.300 --> 03:54.600
On the wall,
beneath the shotgun.

03:54.602 --> 03:56.435
Is there gas in the engine?

03:56.437 --> 03:58.437
Filled it this morning when
I filled myself with coffee.

03:58.439 --> 04:00.872
Do we have food enough
to last a week-long stakeout?

04:00.874 --> 04:02.574
Rotten crabs
that'll make you upchuck

04:02.576 --> 04:05.344
over the side of the boat
after every meal.

04:05.346 --> 04:08.480
And lots and lots of cigarettes
to get the taste of smelly crab

04:08.482 --> 04:10.782
and fresh vomit
out of your mouth.

04:10.784 --> 04:13.752
Well, then let's go cut off
a mermaid's tail then.

04:13.754 --> 04:16.588
<i> ¶¶ [upbeat]</i>

04:16.589 --> 04:19.725
<i> ¶ I like a song</i>
<i> with a skip-a-dee-dee ¶</i>

04:19.726 --> 04:23.395
<i> ¶ When the melody</i>
<i> moves right along ¶</i>

04:23.397 --> 04:26.865
<i> ¶ The kind of a tune</i>
<i> you can tap with your feet ¶</i>

04:26.867 --> 04:30.335
<i> ¶ I love</i>
<i> an old-fashioned song ¶</i>

04:30.337 --> 04:31.937
<i> ¶ La la la la la ¶</i>

04:31.939 --> 04:34.673
<i> ¶¶ [continues]</i>

04:50.424 --> 04:51.790
Hi, Susan?

04:51.792 --> 04:54.893
Susan, it's Dr. Beyer.
Connect me to Markham.

04:54.895 --> 04:55.994
Hold on a second.

05:01.835 --> 05:03.669
Yeah, two.

05:03.671 --> 05:05.370
Thank you.

05:05.372 --> 05:08.507
[seagulls cawing]

05:27.761 --> 05:30.062
The birds are tugging
on the net.

05:42.609 --> 05:46.044
Turn the engine off, so you
don't scare away the mermaids.

05:47.781 --> 05:50.015
Start her up,
check the engine.

05:51.852 --> 05:54.986
Knock anything off that
might be growing on her.

05:54.988 --> 05:56.621
[engine stops]

06:01.462 --> 06:04.029
This boat's been quiet
for longer sits.

06:05.766 --> 06:08.767
Put an Alvey out there.

06:08.769 --> 06:12.704
Baitcaster, barrel, berley,

06:12.706 --> 06:16.475
bobby cork,

06:16.477 --> 06:18.043
droppers, pollards.

06:18.045 --> 06:19.978
Engine doesn't
scare away the birds.

06:19.980 --> 06:21.713
[cawing]

06:26.487 --> 06:28.687
Engine doesn't
scare away the birds.

06:37.731 --> 06:39.831
Chrome slicers,

06:39.833 --> 06:42.667
flies, gang hooks.

06:59.620 --> 07:01.153
Okay, well...

07:02.623 --> 07:03.755
MOSS: Starboard!

07:03.757 --> 07:05.657
STANLEY: Got her!
Get the net!

07:06.693 --> 07:08.794
[shouting]

07:14.067 --> 07:15.567
Over here!

07:19.773 --> 07:21.606
[engine starts]

07:23.010 --> 07:26.945
[squealing]

07:29.817 --> 07:32.617
STANLEY: Pull her up!
Pull her up!

07:34.054 --> 07:37.189
<i> ¶¶ [lounge]</i>

07:43.797 --> 07:45.997
Oh, shit, pull her up!

07:52.072 --> 07:53.905
Get the crank!

07:58.779 --> 08:00.545
[engine idling]

08:00.547 --> 08:03.715
<i> ¶¶ [continues]</i>

08:31.178 --> 08:32.244
[squeals]

08:42.688 --> 08:44.823
[panting]

08:48.595 --> 08:49.728
[splash]

08:49.730 --> 08:50.795
[grunts]

09:00.741 --> 09:03.909
[panting]

09:15.689 --> 09:17.088
Hey, help, man!

09:22.896 --> 09:25.764
[squeals]

09:26.900 --> 09:28.867
- [bones crunch]
- [Moss screams]

09:30.637 --> 09:33.271
[squealing]

09:35.208 --> 09:38.109
[snarling]

09:49.823 --> 09:51.823
Come here, bitch.

09:56.196 --> 10:00.231
- [straining]
- [squealing]

10:08.909 --> 10:10.909
STANLEY: Oh, shit!

10:18.218 --> 10:19.351
Shit!

10:22.956 --> 10:25.223
Stop her from going overboard!
I didn't tie her off yet!

10:25.225 --> 10:27.892
- [yelling]
- [splash]

10:57.791 --> 10:59.858
[yelling]

